Basic plot operations in Seaborn¶

In [19]:
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

Before we look at the various plot types, take note of the imported the packages in the first code cell above. Seaborn depends on Matplotlib, so we import it along with seaborn. We also import seaborn as sns. This convention is standard accross all seaborn documentation, so it's a good idea to get in the habbit of importing the packages this way.

Simple plots¶

Setup a couple of simple dataframes

In [20]:
df2 = pd.DataFrame({'X':[0,1,2,3,4,5,6,7,8], 'Y':[0,1,4,9,16,25,36,49,64]})
df3 = pd.DataFrame({'X':[0,1,2,3,4,5,6,7,8], 'Y':[0,1,8,27,64,125,216,343,512]})

Scatterplot¶

Make a scatter plot in seaborn, note that most plots in seaborn take a dataframe as an argument and you simply supply the column names you want in the plot.

In [21]:
sns.scatterplot(data=df2, x='X', y='Y')
Out[21]:
<AxesSubplot:xlabel='X', ylabel='Y'>

Line plot¶

In [22]:
sns.lineplot(data=df2, x='X', y='Y')
Out[22]:
<AxesSubplot:xlabel='X', ylabel='Y'>

Bar plot¶

In [23]:
sns.barplot(data=df2, x='X', y='Y')
Out[23]:
<AxesSubplot:xlabel='X', ylabel='Y'>

Adjusting plot parameters¶

Labels and limits¶

Let's add some labels and adjust the axis limits

In [24]:
sns.lineplot(data=df2, x='X', y='Y')

plt.xlim([0,10])
plt.ylim([0,100])
plt.title('A Plot of Squares')
plt.xlabel('Number')
plt.ylabel('Squares')
Out[24]:
Text(0, 0.5, 'Squares')

Figure size¶

Let's make the figure a bit bigger, in order to do so we have to use matplotlib's figure before our plot call.

In [25]:
plt.figure(figsize=[15,8])
sns.lineplot(data=df2, x='X', y='Y')
Out[25]:
<AxesSubplot:xlabel='X', ylabel='Y'>

Overlaying multiple plots¶

Let's plot two things on top of each other, to do so just call the plotting function twice. We can use plt.legend to add a figure legend.

In [26]:
sns.lineplot(data=df2, x='X', y='Y')
sns.lineplot(data=df3, x='X', y='Y')

plt.legend(labels=['Square', 'Cube'])
Out[26]:
<matplotlib.legend.Legend at 0x7fcfd448f490>

Histograms¶

Let's make a new dataframe with two columns, each having a normal distribution of random values but with different widths/centers.

In [27]:
df=pd.DataFrame({'Norm1':np.random.normal(4,1,1000), 'Norm2':np.random.normal(3,3,1000)})

Displot¶

In [71]:
sns.displot?

Let's plot a simple histogram using displot.

In [60]:
sns.displot(data=df, x='Norm1')
Out[60]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.FacetGrid at 0x7fcfd887fa10>

Let's make it prettier by adding an estimator line using kde=True, a rug at the bottom using rug=True, specifying the bins, and the size of the figure using height.

In [67]:
sns.displot(data=df, x='Norm1', kde=True, rug=True, bins=np.arange(0,8,0.5), height=8, color='r')
Out[67]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.FacetGrid at 0x7fcfbb27f650>

If we want to overlay two histograms, there are several ways to accomplish this, we'll start with displot. The easiest way to do this is to melt our dataframe so that we can use hue= to separate them.

In [68]:
df.melt()
Out[68]:
variable value
0 Norm1 5.240752
1 Norm1 3.412724
2 Norm1 3.209622
3 Norm1 5.138136
4 Norm1 4.412464
... ... ...
1995 Norm2 3.180141
1996 Norm2 1.228859
1997 Norm2 1.049885
1998 Norm2 3.712827
1999 Norm2 7.659942

2000 rows 2 columns

In [70]:
sns.displot(data=df.melt(), x='value', hue='variable', height=8)
Out[70]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.FacetGrid at 0x7fcfbb5c4b50>

The last plot shows us the distribution of the two variables, but what about their relationship? For that we can use the y= argument of displot.

In [12]:
sns.displot(df, x='Norm1', y='Norm2')
Out[12]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.FacetGrid at 0x7fcfd3036e50>

For this dataset it is not too interesting, let's put together two separate datasets with different means and standard deviations for our two variables.

In [13]:
df_A = pd.DataFrame({'Norm1':np.random.normal(4,1,1000), 'Norm2':np.random.normal(3,3,1000), 'Type':'A'})
df_B = pd.DataFrame({'Norm1':np.random.normal(2,1,1000), 'Norm2':np.random.normal(5,3,1000), 'Type':'B'})
In [14]:
df_AB = pd.concat([df_A, df_B])

Now when we plot we provide the hue argument to see which distribution it came from.

In [15]:
sns.displot(df_AB, x='Norm1', y='Norm2', hue='Type')
Out[15]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.FacetGrid at 0x7fcfd3024bd0>

Unfortunately this can cover up data, use the "kind" argument helps with clarity

In [16]:
sns.displot(df_AB, x='Norm1', y='Norm2', hue='Type', kind='kde')
Out[16]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.FacetGrid at 0x7fcfd3248ad0>

Jointplot¶

Sometimes it is useful to have the 1D distributions as well, jointplot can do that for us.

In [17]:
plt.figure(figsize=[15,8])
sns.jointplot(data=df_AB, x='Norm1', y='Norm2', hue='Type', kind='kde')
Out[17]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.JointGrid at 0x7fcfd369fa90>
<Figure size 1080x576 with 0 Axes>

Let's go back to a scatterplot, but make the points larger using joint_kws. We'll also format using xlim, ylim, and height.

In [72]:
plt.figure(figsize=[15,8])
sns.jointplot(data=df_AB, x='Norm1', y='Norm2', hue='Type', height=12, joint_kws={"s":300}, xlim=[-2,7], ylim=[-5,15])

<Figure size 1080x576 with 0 Axes>

Saving figures¶

The easieset way to save figures is to call a matplotlib function right after the last plotting function is called.

In [73]:
plt.figure(figsize=[15,8])
sns.jointplot(data=df_AB, x='Norm1', y='Norm2', hue='Type', height=12, joint_kws={"s":300}, xlim=[-2,7], ylim=[-5,15])
plt.savefig('output.pdf')

<Figure size 1080x576 with 0 Axes>
